Bolter
Hook Skip: The tailhook bounced over the arresting wires.
Foul Deck: The landing area was not clear for landing (e.g., another aircraft or debris). Usually results in a waveoff.
No Ball: Pilot did not call the "ball" (glide slope indicator) in sight at the appropriate time.
Pilot reports not having visual contact with the ball.
Indicates which arresting wire was caught (e.g., "Wire 1," "Wire 2," "Wire 3"). A "3-wire" catch is generally considered ideal.
Eased Guns In Wires: Pilot reduced power while still in the wires, which is dangerous. Often results in a "No Grade" or worse.
After Wires: Something happened after the aircraft engaged the wires.
Three Point Strike: Aircraft landed with all three landing gear touching down simultaneously, which can be hard on the nose gear.
In Close.
Too Much Rate of Descent In Close: Excessive sink rate very near touchdown.
Slow At the Start: Aircraft was slow at the beginning of the approach.
Low In the Middle: Aircraft was below the glide path in the middle of the approach.
Low In Close: Aircraft was below the glide path near touchdown.
Lined Up Right At the Start: Aircraft was misaligned to the right at the beginning.
Drifted Right At the Start: Aircraft was drifting to the right early in the approach.
Fast At the Start: Aircraft was too fast at the beginning.
Lined Up Right In the Middle: Aircraft was misaligned to the right in the middle.
Drifted Left In Close: Aircraft was drifting to the left near touchdown.
Lined Up Left In Middle: Aircraft was misaligned to the left in the middle.
Lined Up Right In Close: Aircraft was misaligned to the right near touchdown.
Wave Off (All Fouled Up) In Close: A waveoff due to a significant issue very near the carrier.
Landed Right To Land: Aircraft touched down significantly to the right of the centerline.
